      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/python-data-structure-verification/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The function builds a spatial graph and saves its adjacency and weighted adjacency matrices to adata.obsp['spatial_connectivities'] in either Numpy or Scipy sparse arrays. The weights of the weighted adjacency matrix are distances in the case of coord_type = 'generic' and ordinal numbers of hexagonal rings in the case of coord_type = 'grid'. Together with the connectivities, we also provide a sparse adjacency matrix of distances, saved in adata.obsp['spatial_distances']",
      "asbval:note": "Paper demonstrates explicit storage of results in named AnnData attributes with specified data types (sparse arrays), supporting the validation workflow described.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41592-021-01358-2",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "python-data-structure-verification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "After executing a spatial analysis function (e.g., squidpy.gr.sepal) that modifies or augments a data object, verify that the expected output fields exist with correct names, data types, and array dimensions before proceeding to interpretation or visualization.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:10:43.158352+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/python-data-structure-verification/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Squidpy is extensible and can be interfaced with a variety of already existing libraries for the scalable analysis of spatial omics data. Its modularity makes it suitable to be interfaced with a variety of additional tools in the Python data science and machine-learning ecosystem (such as external segmentation methods and modern deep-learning frameworks), as well as several single-cell data analysis packages.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper emphasizes Squidpy's extensibility and integration with external tools, supporting the use case of validating outputs from integrated workflows.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41592-021-01358-2",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "python-data-structure-verification",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Use this skill when integrating third-party spatial tools into a workflow and you need confidence that results conform to a documented schema.",
